snippet.textDisplay:
Or we getting over excited?

Was Wilder that good?

I mean who has he really fought?

Ortiz was an old man, that gave Wilder hell in two fights

Tyson was Wilder's first big test and he failed it badly. twice.

In fact he lost the first fight.

That said, he was obviously a very dangerous puncher, that Joshua was in no hurry to fight. And Tyson went in the lion's den and took the belt.

So hyoe about Wilder aside, being the greatest puncher in heavyweight history - rather than a novice, raw, one trick pony - still a great performance by Fury.

But Joshua vs Fury was and remains the real fight of the era.

snippet.textDisplay: Fury is top 3 heavyweights of ALL TIME, not just the greatest today. Think about it: when has Ali ever fought someone as big (6’9”), fast, powerful, and defensively skillful as Fury? Never- not even close. The Fury we saw against Wilder II would bully Ali and drain him. The ONLY heavyweights in history that would give Fury a serious challenge and threat are LEWIS and VITALI KLITSCHKO. That’s it. Not even prime Mike Tyson could take down Fury. Personally, I feel the top 3 of all time are Vitali, Lewis, and Fury (1, 2, 3), in that order. If Fury beats Joshua and Whyte convincingly, I might move Fury up to the #2 or even #1 spot.

My only problem here or well.. I guess my only 2 problems are 1. Why the clear behind the ear shot that had his ear leaking like a faucet obviously taking away his equilibrium (making things like balance and that thing some of us need in boxing called the ability to stand and walk) non existent, is getting zero talk whatsoever especially when it was so early in the fight. Ofcourse hes not gonna be the same Wilder, and Fury basically gets to hold bag practice for the rest of the fight.
And 2. More importantly is how fkn sad the majority of fans have been since saying ridiculous things like Wilder was a fluke, hes a bumb, was never a great fighter, and much worse. Idk.. at the end of the day I'm personally not invested either way, not a diehard fan of either man but taking a look at all this from a step back reveals a sad and disgusting truth at how unrealistic and blind the majority of boxing fans are in 2020..
